Help Type: command
Command: wikigraph queue

Purpose:
  Manage device-local generation tasks for `.sdpub` chapters.

Usage:
  wikigraph queue add <archive.sdpub> --chapter <id> --task <reading-graph|reading-summary|knowledge-graph> --accept-cost [--boost] [--llm <json>] [--prompt <text>]
  wikigraph queue list [--all] [--active] [--input <archive.sdpub>]
  wikigraph queue status <job-id>
  wikigraph queue watch <job-id> [--jsonl] [--from beginning|now]
  wikigraph queue pause <job-id>
  wikigraph queue resume <job-id>
  wikigraph queue cancel <job-id>
  wikigraph queue boost <job-id>
  wikigraph queue target <job-id> --task <reading-graph|reading-summary|knowledge-graph>
  wikigraph queue clean

Tasks:
  - reading-graph builds the reading-oriented chunk graph from sourced text.
  - reading-summary builds summaries from the Reading Graph. It builds reading-graph first when needed.
  - knowledge-graph builds entity mentions from sourced text. Use this before searching `--type entity`.

Task shape:
  - reading-graph -> reading-summary is the Reading Graph line.
  - knowledge-graph is separate and does not build summaries.
  - Queue one task per chapter. Add both reading-summary and knowledge-graph when you need both outputs.

Cost:
  Queue tasks may call an LLM, consume tokens, and incur provider charges.
  `queue add` requires `--accept-cost`.

Examples:
  wikigraph queue add book.sdpub --chapter 3 --task reading-graph --accept-cost
  wikigraph queue add book.sdpub --chapter 3 --task reading-summary --accept-cost
  wikigraph queue add book.sdpub --chapter 3 --task knowledge-graph --accept-cost
  wikigraph queue watch <job-id> --jsonl
